<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="prep-10-9">
  <title>Resources for 10/9</title>

  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Solve application problems where functions are created by adding, subtracting, multiplying, and dividing other functions.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Determine the formulas and input values for a piecewise defined function, given appropriate information about the function.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Sketch the graph of a piecewise defined function.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-combining-applications-2">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Applications of Combining Functions (Continued from Last Class)</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on <em>combining functions in applications</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="mQKiX9OGViY" />

    <problem>
      <title>Combining Functions (Applications)</title>
      <p>
        Create the following functions and solve the application problems.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Jojo is selling fancy chairs.  If the price is <m>p</m> dollars, Jojo can sell <m>d(p) = 900-3p</m> units.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    If Jojo sells their chairs for <m>p = $3</m>, what is the total revenue that Jojo takes in?  Do the same for <m>p=$10</m> and <m>p = $20</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Use the same reasoning as in (a) to find a formula for Jojo's total revenue when the price is <m>p</m>.  We will call the total revenue <m>R(p)</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What are the domain and range of <m>R(p)</m>?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              You are building a rectangular fenced-in space for your dog right next to your home with 100 feet of fencing.  One of the sides of the area is the side of your home.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    If <m>x</m> is the length of one of the sides of the fence that is attached to your home, and if <m>y</m> is the length of the side not attached to your home, what is the area of the fenced-in space?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    If the length of one of the sides of the fence that is attached to your home is <m>x</m>, what is the area <m>A(x)</m> of the fenced-in space?  Hint:  Let <m>y</m> be the length of the side not attached to your home, and solve for <m>y</m> in terms of <m>x</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    If the length of the side of the fence not touching your home is <m>y</m>, what is the area <m>a(y)</m> of the fenced in space?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What are the domain and range of the above functions?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </problem>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-piecewise">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Piecewise Defined Functions</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on <em>piecewise defined functions</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="SC8BOx7TSuA" />

    <problem>
      <title>Piecewise Defined Functions</title>
      <p>
        Consider the functions below.  The middle part of the second graph is a parabola.
      </p>
      <sidebyside widths="45% 45%">
        <image>
        	<prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="piecewise-graph-prep-1">
		        <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
			        <definition>f(x)= -2*(x+4)+1</definition>
        			<definition>g(x)=(1/3)*(x-4)+1</definition>
		        	<coordinates bbox="(-5,-4,5,2)">
				        <axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
    				    <graph function="f" domain="(-4,-2)"/>
    		    		<graph function="g" domain="(-2,4)"/>
    				    <point p="(-4,1)" fill="blue" stroke="blue"> <m>(-4,1)</m> </point>
        				<point p="(-2,-3)" fill="blue" stroke="blue" alignment="s"> <m>(-2,-3)</m> </point>
            		<point p="(-2,-1)" fill="white" stroke="blue" alignment="s"> <m>(-2,-1)</m> </point>
    		    		<point p="(4,1)" fill="blue" stroke="blue" alignment="nw"> <m>(4,1)</m> </point>
    			    </coordinates>
    		    </diagram>
    	    </prefigure>
        </image>
        <image>
    	    <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="piecewise-graph-prep-2">
        		<diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
    		    	<definition>f(x)= -3*(x+3)+4</definition>
    			    <definition>g(x)=-1.5*(x-1)^2+4</definition>
        			<definition>h(x)= 0.5*(x-5)+4</definition>
    		    	<coordinates bbox="(-4,-3,6,5)">
    				    <axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
        				<graph function="f" domain="(-3,-1)"/>
    		    		<graph function="g" domain="(-1,2)"/>
    				    <graph function="h" domain="(2,5)" />
        				<point p="(-3,4)"> <m>(-3,4)</m> </point>
    		    		<point p="(-1,-2)" alignment="nw"> <m>(-1,-2)</m> </point>
    				    <point p="(1,4)" alignment="ne"> <m>(1,4)</m> </point>
        				<point p="(2,2.5)" alignment="s"> <m>(2,2.5)</m> </point>
    		    		<point p="(5,4)" alignment="n"> <m>(5,4)</m> </point>
    			    </coordinates>
    		    </diagram>
    	    </prefigure>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Determine the formula(s) for each function above.  For the parabola, I suggest using the vertex form of the formula.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Consider the following piecewise defined function.
        <md>f(x) = \left\{ \begin{matrix} 2x+3 &amp; x &lt; 1 \\ (x-2)^2+1 &amp; 1 \le x \le 3 \\ -x+5 &amp; x>3 \end{matrix} \right.</md>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Compute <m>f(-2)</m>, <m>f(2)</m>, and <m>f(5)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Sketch a graph of <m>f</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </problem>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

